KwaZulu-Natal (KZN) Health MEC, Nomagugu Simelane-Zulu has assured KZN residents that the province has a plan for the informal settlements should the COVID-19 disease escalate. Simelane-Zulu was addressing the media at the Hilton hotel in Durban on Monday, 16 March. This comes after the President declared a National State of Disaster on Sunday, 15 March. Simelane-Zulu said that the Departments of Health and Public Works and Human Settlements will work together to identify areas that are deemed informal settlements. “If necessary, we will move the infected cases from that area into isolation, ” she said. Simelane-Zulu said that two additional hospitals have been added to the four COVID-19 facilities in the province bringing the total number of COVID-19 dedicated hospitals to six. The two additional hospitals are Doris Goodwin and Richmond Hospital. She also said that there will be COVID-19 dedicated wards inside hospitals in every district. Simelane-Zulu  explained the difference between quarantine and isolation as follows: Simelane-Zulu mentioned that those who test positive for COVID-19 and refuse to go into isolation will be ordered to by the courts. She also emphasized the importance of hygiene precautions such as washing hands with soap, using sanitisers, and keeping a social distance of 1.5 metres.